\begin_layout Abstract
This report describes the work of implementing a number of robots who cooperativ
ely searches for a non-cooperative target.
 Robots collect data using low resolution cameras and odometers mounted
 inside the wheel motors.
 Collected data is then processed and used for robot positioning and target
 tracking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Report describes two target tracking filters.
 First one is based on Kalman filter theory and the other one is based on
 Particle filter theory.
 Both filters were developed side by side to compare different mathematical
 tools implemented in an embedded device.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Tracking can only be done successfully if robots know their approximate
 position.
 Relying only on odometer data gave positioning results with an error steadily
 increasing over time.
 This problem was solved with an Geometric filter which uses data collected
 about landmarks which are light emitting towers standing at known locations.
\end_layout

